~/.ollama/models/blobs directory (5 multi-GB GGUFs found: 2 gemma4, 1 gemma3,
1 llama-3-8B-instruct, 1 phi4-mini-reasoning).

TEST A — Stratify byte entropy by quantization type within ONE gemma4 model:
           qtype=F32   n= 87  mean=2.9649  std=0.9953
           qtype=Q4_K  n= 98  mean=7.7667  std=0.0414   ← variance ≈ 0
           qtype=Q6_K  n= 16  mean=7.9281  std=0.0033   ← variance ≈ 0
         → Within a quant type, entropy is essentially a CONSTANT.
         → The 7.7-7.9 band is the signature of the Q-K quantization SCHEME,
           which is designed to use the byte space efficiently.
         → AG31's "RLHF distortion signal" is the Q4_K codec.

TEST B — Cross-model comparison:
           gemma4    mean=5.6385  std=2.5252  qtypes=[F32,Q4_K,Q6_K]
           llama-3   mean=6.4645  std=1.8523  qtypes=[F32,Q4_0]    ← different qtypes
           gemma3    mean=7.3796  std=0.5484  qtypes=[F32,Q4_K,Q6_K]
         → Models differ mostly in their quant-type MIX, not in their
           "biological vs trained" signature.

TEST C — Dequantize ONE Q4_K tensor and compute entropy on real fp32 weights:
           tensor: blk.0.attn_q.weight (Q4_K)
             raw byte entropy    = 7.7806 bits/byte   ← what AG31 reports
             dequant fp32 entropy = 5.8233 bits        ← what actually matters
             real weight stats: mean=-1.28e-5  std=2.76e-2  min=-0.259  max=+0.255
         → THIS is the kind of number that could carry an RLHF signature.
         → AG31's scanner never computes it.

CONCLUSION: `swarm_weight_space_scan.py` does succeed at TOUCHING the
disk-resident weights (which is more than `connectome_harmonics.py` did),
but its observable is the wrong observable. It's measuring the entropy of
the codec, not the entropy of the network.

